Knorr and his partner blinded the birds with a flashlight, caught four adult birds and one chick, descended with them to the bottom of the canyon, ringed and released the adult birds, and then returned the chick to the nest. Knorr formulated criteria for finding suitable places for a colony of black American swifts, which subsequently followed by many ornithologists. After publishing in The Auk in 1950, Knorr received suggestions from egg hunters and took great care to ensure that the description of the exact locations of the colonies was rather vague. specialists with binoculars came to the researchers with guns. According to Ludlow Griscom, “rarely does a trained person need to shoot a bird in order to accurately identify it” (eng.